## Migration: `Thread.Abort` Timeout → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006). The replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with task-based execution.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // Caller cancelled — propagate
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| **Work ignores cancellation** | If `work` is a long loop, it must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. Cooperative cancellation won't interrupt CPU-bound code that never checks. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking causes timer/callback leaks. |
| **Blocking I/O won't stop** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive` etc. won't respond to token. Use async I/O with token or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch at the orchestration boundary. Let it propagate through the call chain. |

### For Truly Uncooperative Code

If `work` calls third-party code you **cannot modify** to accept a token, the only safe option is process isolation:

```csharp
// Move uncooperative work to a child process and use Process.Kill on timeout
```

### What Was Removed

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |

The fundamental shift: cancellation is now **cooperative** — your work must voluntarily check the token. There is no way to forcibly inject an exception into a running thread in modern .NET.
